land continues to operate in the long shadow of its own turbulent past. Those who were victims of violence, as well as those who were its agents, have often been consigned to the margins of a society still struggling to cope with the traumas of the Troubles. Furthermore, the transition to ‘peace’ has revealed the existence of new, and not so new, forms of violence in Northern Irish society, directed towards women, ethnic minorities and the poor.Northern Ireland a generation after Good Friday sets out to capture the complex, and often contradictory, realities that have emerged more than two decades on from the region’s vaunted peace deal. Across nine original essays, the authors offer a critical and comprehensive reading of a society that often appears to have left its violent past behind but at the same time remains subject to its gravitational pull.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPeace-buildingzNorthern Ireland. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh  aBrexit.  acinema.  aconsociationalism.  aconstiutional change.  aethno-nationalism.  apeace processes.  apolitical economy.  aprisoners.  atelevision.  avictims.  awomen.1 aGilmartin, Niall, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHayward, Katy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613927640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526139276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526139276/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles